<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Look for Extended Lees Aging</strong> - The best Champagnes spend significantly longer on their lees than the minimum 15 months required. Seek bottles with 3-7 years on lees, indicated by terms like "vieillissement prolongé" or by researching the producer's disgorgement dates. This extended aging creates the creamy, brioche-like complexity that separates exceptional Champagne from basic versions.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 46-50°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Best Champagnes reveal their complexity when served slightly warmer than standard sparkling wines. At 46-50°F, premium bottles from houses like Krug or Dom Pérignon showcase their full aromatic profile, while maintaining proper mousse. Too cold (below 45°F) and you'll miss the nuanced secondary and tertiary aromas that justify the price.</li>

  <li><strong>Never Decant, But Do Consider Riddling Position Storage</strong> - Unlike still wines, even the finest vintage Champagnes should never be decanted as this destroys the carefully preserved carbon dioxide. However, store your best bottles neck-down (sur pointe) for 24 hours before serving to allow any sediment from recent disgorgement to settle in the neck.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Proper Flute or Tulip Glasses, Never Coupes</strong> - Best Champagnes demand glassware that preserves their mousse and concentrates aromatics. Choose thin-rimmed flutes or tulip-shaped glasses with a capacity of 6-7 ounces. The narrow opening maintains CO2 pressure while the bowl shape allows swirling to release complex esters and aldehydes that develop during extended aging.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand Disgorgement Dates for Peak Drinking</strong> - Premium Champagnes are at their peak 6 months to 2 years after disgorgement. Look for the disgorgement date (often coded as "D" followed by numbers) on the back label. Recently disgorged bottles may taste tight and benefit from 3-6 months of rest, while those disgorged over 3 years ago may have lost some of their vibrant effervescence.</li>

  <li><strong>Recognize Grower Champagne Quality Indicators</strong> - The best grower Champagnes (marked "RM" for Récoltant-Manipulant) often represent exceptional value. Look for producers from Grand Cru villages like Ay, Cramant, or Le Mesnil-sur-Oger who estate-bottle single-vineyard expressions. These bottles showcase terroir more distinctly than many grande marque blends.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Prestige Cuvées for Proper Maturity</strong> - Best Champagnes like Dom Pérignon, Cristal, or Winston Churchill are designed for extended aging. Vintage prestige cuvées typically need 8-15 years from vintage date to reach full complexity, developing honeyed, mushroom, and mineral notes. Don't open these immediately after purchase unless the vintage is already properly mature.</li>

  <li><strong>Master the Proper Opening Technique</strong> - Best Champagnes deserve careful opening to preserve their mousse and prevent waste. Chill thoroughly, remove foil completely, hold the cork while turning the bottle (not the cork), and aim for a gentle "whisper" rather than a pop. The goal is to maintain maximum CO2 pressure and present the wine with its full effervescent potential intact.</li>
</ol>





